 
    The following documentation is meant to explain the use of the vehicle
inheritable.  First, please understand what the inheritable is meant to do
so you aren't using it for the wrong reason.  A vehicle, in the sense of the
inheritable is some object that a player or multiple players can use to 
travel around the mud.  It can also store things for that player, and be used
as a symbol of power.
    This actual inheritable creates the outside appearance of that vehicle.
Then, using a vehicle room inheritable, you can create a single, or multiple
rooms for that vehicle.  The 'hull' of the vehicle actually clones the rooms
to it, and then travels around with that group of objects, including players
and their inventories.
    I will attempt to explain how to use this inheritable for one or multi-room
vehicles.  These vehicles will check direction hooks for all players on the
vehicle at the time, and they will check for legal terrain, in the next room.
Aside from those slight restrictions, it is basically something you can ride
around the mud in.  
    The vehicle consists of several files.  You have to have the actual vehicle
object.  Then, for each 'room' within the vehicle, you will need a file.  Lastly
there is a sort of driver for the vehicle's rooms, that you will need to code.
    This is a little more complicated than your average lpc coding.  If you are 
a little confused, you can find example files in /public/docs/vehicles:
    test.c     == The vehicle object.
    front.c    == A front room for the vehicle.
    back.c     == A back room for the vehicle.
    standard.c == That vehicle's standard addition file.
 
********************************************************************************
The Vehicle Object:
 
    The vehicle will be an object that noone ever enters.  That is the object 
that will inherit VEHICLE.  This will NOT inherit ROOM or anything else.  You 
will define all the strings there, such as the movement messages, its name,
short and long descriptions, etc.  Each room should not do this.  
 
Always #include <mudlib.h> and then just inherit VEHICLE;
 
Your reset function should have a ::reset();  as should your init have ::init();
You need to init_vehicle(); at the *end* of your reset function.
 
void set_name(string str);
  The string you pass is the name of the vehicle.  
 
    set_name("ship");
 
string query_name(string str);
  Returns the ship's name.
    
    query_name();
 
void set_alias(string str);
  The string you pass is an alias for the vehicle.  
  To set multiple alias's just set_alias again.
    
    Single:   set_alias("ship");
    Multiple: set_alias(({"ship","vehicle"}));
 
varargs mixed query_alias(string str);
  Returns the array of alias' if nothing is passed.
  Returns 1 if str is a valid alias set for this vehicle.
 
    query_alias();
    query_alias("vehicle");
 
void set_short(string str);
  This is the short description you will see outside of the vehicle.
 
    set_short("Vehicle");
 
string short();
  Returns the vehicle's short description.
 
    short();
 
int id(string str);
  Returns 1 if the str passed is a valid id.
 
    id("vehicle");
 
void set_long(string str);
  This is the long description you will see outside of the vehicle.
 
    set_long("A great looking vehicle.\n");
 
string query_long();
  Returns the long description of the vehicle.
 
    query_long();
 
void long(string str);
  Returns the long of the vehicle or of an add_look.
 
    long("vehicle");
 
int query_level();
  For dir_hooks it returns APPRENTICE;
 
    query_level();
 
void set_arrival(string str);
  This is the string shown when the vehicle arrives in a room.
 
    set_arrival("The vehicle arrives.\n");
 
void set_departure(string str);
  This is the string shown when the vehicle leaves the room.
 
    set_departure("The vehicle leaves"); 
    NOTE:  Do not attach a '.' or a '\n' because the direction which the 
    vehicle leaves, is added to the end of this string.
 
void set_max_players(int i);
  This is the maximum number of people allowed on the vehicle.
  You *must* set this variable.  It must be an appropriate size.
              For example, a horse would only accept two players.
 
    set_max_players(10);
 
void set_bad_terrain(mixed str);
  You use this function to set up an array of terrains that this 
  vehicle cannot travel in.  Like the set_alias function, you can 
  pass an array for multiple bad terrains.
 
    Single:   set_bad_terrain("inside");
    Multiple: set_bad_terrain(({"inside","city"}));
 
void add_look(string *name, string desc);
  If you describe an object on the outside of the vehicle, this would
  be the description for that object.  You can pass an array as the first
  argument.
 
    add_look("mast","The mast is extremely tall.\n");
    add_look(({"mast","masts"}),"They are tall.\n");
 
void set_rooms_path(string str);
  This is the path to the rooms of your vehicle.
 
    set_rooms_path("/players/myname/vehicle/rooms/");
 
string query_rooms_path();
  Returns the rooms path of the vehicle.
   
    query_rooms_path();
 
void set_addition_path(string str);
  This is the path to your addition file (standard.c).
 
    set_addition_path("/players/myname/vehicle/");
 
string *query_additions();
  Returns the array of addition files.
 
    query_additions();
 
void add_addition(string str);
  This is the 'daemon' that sets up the rooms for your vehicle.
  You can add as many as you want.  In other words, if you want
  to have different vehicles, with a different set of rooms, you 
  can have a different addition file for it.  This must be called
  after the addition path is set.
 
    add_addition("standard.c");
    NOTE:  You must add_addition the file that you have setup to clone the
           vehicle's rooms.  
 
int query_addition(string str);
  Returns 1 if the str is an addition of that vehicle.
 
    query_addition("standard.c");
 
void remove_addition(string str);
  Removes that addition for that vehicle.
 
    remove_addtion("standard.c");
 
string query_addition_path();
  Returns the addition path.
    
    query_addition_path();
 
void set_owner(string str);
  This is the name of the owner of the vehicle, if its owned.
  This should be used if its a player owned vehicle only.
 
    set_owner("player_name");
 
string query_owner();
  Returns the name of the owner.
   
    query_owner();
 
object find_owner();
  Returns the object that owns the vehicle, if its online.
 
    find_owner();
 
varargs void tell_vehicle(string str, string *exclude);
  The first argument is what to be told to the vehicle, and the second argument
  is an array of string, exclusions, what rooms *not* to tell the string to.
  You don't always have to pass the second argument.  If for some reason you 
  want to set_listen in this room, differently than the rest of the vehicle, 
  you can set_listen(0) or 1 as needed.  (1 listens)
 
The only other special actions in the inheritable is that for 'enter_func'. 
It is not defined as an add_action in the inheritable, so you will have to 
add_action it yourself in your init of your vehicle object.  The purpose here,
was to allow you to define your own type of function for boarding (IE a horse
would be mount.)  
 
If you wish to use your vehicle for combat, and allow it to have vehicle_points,
similar to hit_points on a player, use the following functions, much like those
in living.c:
 
  void set_max_vp(int iArg);
  int query_max_vp();
  void restore_vp(int iArg);
  int query_vp();
 
Currently there is no support for vehicle vs. vehicle combat.  If you wish to 
do something like that, you will have to prototype that yourself.  There are
no funtions within that will help, except for the four listed above.
 
If you'd like to use access lists in your vehicle, use the following functions:
 
void use_access(int iX);
  Set this to 1 if you want to use access lists.
 
int add_access(string name)
  Add name to your access list.
 
int remove_access(string name)
  Remove name from your access list.
 
mixed query_access(string name)
  If name is passed it will check to see if name has access to the vehicle, 
  returning a 1 if so, 0 otherwise.  If nothing is passed it will return the
  array access_list containing everyone with access.
 
********************************************************************************
The Vehicle Room Daemon:
 
Technically, this is not a daemon, but it sets up the rooms of the vehicle.
You will be better off, calling it an 'additions' file.  This file must be in 
the addition path you set.  The reason for having a separate file to add 
rooms, is so you can have one file, to add a typical set of rooms, to different
vehicles.  Each vehicle must have a standard set of rooms, and it expects you
to add_addition one file in the addition path.  If you wish to only have 1 set 
of rooms, then just make one addition file.  A typical example of the code 
would be this:
 
int do_addition(object oOb) {
  oOb -> add_room("front","front_room");          
    - the first arguement is the unique name of the room, and the second 
    - arguement is the filename of the room, in the rooms path.          
  oOb -> set_entrance("front");
    - You should set the entrance to the vehicle if this is the room you
    - want to be the entrance.                                          
  oOb -> add_room("back","back_room");
  oOb -> add_room("secret","secret_room");
}
 
set_enter_room(n);
  String n.  This is where you enter the vehicle.
 
    set_entrance("front");
    NOTE:  This should always be the only room you enter the vehicle in.
 
********************************************************************************
The Vehicle Rooms:
 
The vehicle clones the 'rooms' of the vehicle to itself.  These rooms should
inherit VEHICLE_ROOM, *not* ROOM.  Each room file has to be in the rooms path
you have previously defined.  Then each room adds an exit to the other rooms,
and the direction function to move the player to that room.  In the add_exit
line of the rooms, you will do something like this:
 
  add_exit("rear","roomname"); 
  Note:  Roomname is the actual roomname of the room, that you set in the
         file of that room.  It will then move the player to the correct room.
         The filename, is that actual filename, not the entire path, so if its
         bridge.c, just use 'bridge' for the second arguement.
 
You will need to set the room's name as well:
  
  set_room_name("rear");
 
object find_room(string str);
  Returns the object of that name, where str is the name of the room.
 
    find_room("room_name");
 
Valid functions to add that are in the inheritable are:
  move_func()              /* Moves the vehicle. */
  leave_func()             /* Leaves the vehicle. */
  look_outside_func()      /* Looks outside the vehicle. */
 
You can just add_action("move_func","steer"); for example, then you might
code a move function to call it, if you want, so you can do your own writes
and says, etc.  Then you can just do move_func(str);
 
As far as the move code is concerned, please do not use your own move function.
This move function correctly checks for terrain, dir_hooks, inits and virtual
rooms.  You can, however, do something like add_action("move","steer");  
(You will have to add_action something for the move command.)  The syntax for
calling move, is just move(string);  The string will be the direction you want
to move in.
 
